               <msContents class="#multipleWorks">
                  <summary>14 works by 9 authors on the subjects of Babism, Muslim saints, Sufism, and Bahai Faith. The <title xml:lang="fa" key="">استدلالیه</title>
                     (<title xml:lang="en">Istidlálíyyih</title>, "Evidences"), a
                     work by <persName key="">Mírzá Abu'l-Fażl of
                        Gulpáygán</persName> intended to prove, from Old Testament
                     quotations and arguments (especially the Book of Daniel), that
                     Bahá'u'lláh is the promised Messiah and deliverer of Israel;
                     addressed chiefly to Jewish readers. Browne judges it was
                     written in AH 1305 (1887-8) on internal evidence.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="F_27-item1" n="1">
                     <author key="person_35791720" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/35791720/">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Abū al-Faḍl Gulpāyigānī,
                           1844-1914</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">ميزا ابو الفضل غلپايگانی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="work_2123">Istidlālīyah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" key="work_2123">استدلالية</title>
                     <title xml:lang="en" type="desc" key="work_2123">Istidlálíyyih
                        (Evidences)</title>
                     <note>Intended to prove, from Old Testament quotations and arguments
                        (especially the Book of Daniel), that Bahá'u'lláh is the promised Messiah
                        and deliverer of Israel; addressed chiefly to Jewish readers. Browne judges
                        it was written in AH 1305 (1887-8) on internal evidence.</note>
                     <note>Structure: a preface (ff. 1a-8a, quoted by Browne in full without
                        translation, "as it is rather interesting") and three sections (maqám): the
                        first (f. 3a of the preface's own foliation) on the general knowability of a
                        prophet's truth; the second (f. 6a) on whether the Mosaic law's fulfilment
                        demands a "new garment" for a new manifestation; the third (f. 11a)
                        surveying scriptural "glad-tidings" concerning such a manifestation, chiefly
                        from the Book of Daniel.</note>
                     <note>Browne highlights a chronological passage (f. 19a) giving Bahá'u'lláh's
                        "Manifestation" as AH 1285 (1868 AD), which he treats as important
                        corroborating evidence for Nabíl's chronology against what he considers the
                        too-early date implied elsewhere by the Traveller's Narrative.</note>
                     <note>Ends with a colophon-like closing formula, "From the pen of Abu'l-Fażl of
                        Gulpáygán."</note>
                     <note>As bound in this composite volume: 22 folios (f. 1a and f. 22b blank),
                        21.25 x 13.25 cm, 14 lines to the page, written in a good, clear Persian
                        ta'líq.</note>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" cert="low" resp="#ocr-draft">اسرائیل عرض میشود که خداوند
                        جل ذکره در ازمان سابقه این طایفهٔ جلیله را بمراتب توحید و خداشناسی هدایت
                        فرمود... (f. 1a)</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa" cert="low" resp="#ocr-draft">... امید چنانست که کل از
                        نصح خالص متنبّه گردند... من قلم ابوالفضل گلپایگانی (f. 22a)</explicit>
                     <listBibl>
                        <bibl>
                           <ref target="https://cudl.lib.cam.ac.uk/view/PR-A-00233-00004/93"
                              >p.67</ref>
                        </bibl>
                        <bibl>See sub classmark <idno>BBS. 1</idno> in Browne's "Catalogue and
                           Description of 27 Bābī Manuscripts (Continuation)", in Journal of the
                           Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland (Oct., 1892):
                           701-703.</bibl>
                        <bibl type="text-relations"/>
                     </listBibl>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
